<pretext>
    <article xml:id="notes">
        <worksheet xml:id="sec-5-1">
        <title><m>\S 5.1</m>: Introduction to Sequences</title>


				<exercise workspace="2in">
					<title>Definitions</title>
					<statement>
						<p>
							A <term>sequence of real numbers</term> is a function
						</p>
					</statement>
				</exercise>

				<exercise>
                    <title>Problems</title>
                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                            Write down several sequences <m>(p_{n})_{n=1}^{\infty}</m> you are familiar with.
If possible, give an algebraic formula for each <m>p_{n}</m> in terms of <m>n</m>.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                            Explain the differences between <m>\{p_{n}\}_{n=1}^{\infty}</m> and <m>(p_{n})_{n=1}^{\infty}</m>.
Give an example of a sequence whose image set is finite.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    
                </exercise>


                <exercise workspace="6in">
					<title>Definitions</title>
					<statement>
						<p>
							We say <m>(p_n)_{n=1}^\infty</m> <term>converges to <m>x \in \mathbb{R}</m></term> if
						</p>
					</statement>
				</exercise>

            <exercise>
                    <title>Problems</title>
                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                           Consider the sequence given by <m>p_{n} = \frac{1}{n}</m>.
Prove that <m>(p_{n})_{n=1}^{\infty}</m> converges to <m>0</m>.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                            Consider the sequence given by <m>p_{n} = 1-\frac{1}{n}</m>.
Prove that <m>(p_{n})_{n=1}^{\infty}</m> converges to <m>1</m>.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                            Consider the sequence with even terms <m>p_{2i}=\frac{1}{2i-1}</m> and odd terms <m>p_{2i-1}= \frac{1}{2i}</m>.
Prove that <m>(p_{n})_{n=1}^{\infty}</m> converges to <m>0</m>.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                            Consider the sequence with odd terms <m>p_{2i-1}=\frac{1}{2i-1}</m> and even terms <m>p_{2i}= 1+\frac{1}{2i}</m>.
Determine whether <m>(p_{n})_{n=1}^{\infty}</m> converges to <m>0</m>.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                            Prove that if <m>(p_{n})_{n=1}^{\infty}</m> converges to the point <m>x</m> <em>and</em> for each <m>n \in \mathbb{N}</m>, <m>p_{n} \neq p_{n+1}</m>, then <m>x</m> is an accumulation point of the image set <m>\{p_{n}\}_{n=1}^{\infty}</m> of the sequence.
Can we weaken the requirement that <m>p_{n} \neq p_{n+1}</m> for all <m>n \in \mathbb{N}</m> and still conclude that <m>x</m> is an accumulation point of the image set?
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                            Prove that if <m>(p_{n})_{n=1}^{\infty}</m> converges to the point <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> is a point different from <m>x</m>, then <m>(p_{n})_{n=1}^{\infty}</m> does <em>not</em> converge to <m>y</m>.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                            Let <m>(p_{n})_{n=1}^{\infty}</m> be a sequence.
Prove that if for every <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m>, there exists <m>N \in \mathbb{N}</m> such that <m>|p_{n}-x| \lt \varepsilon</m> whenever <m>n \geq N</m>, then <m>(p_{n})_{n=1}^{\infty}</m> converges to <m>x</m>.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    
                </exercise>
                

        </worksheet>
    </article>
</pretext>